ITC experiment was performed at 30 °C by titrating 10 mM DNA and its components solution into the GQDs solution in 10 mM phosphate buffer, pH 7.4. The thermodynamic parameters, like enthalpy (ΔH) and entropy (ΔS) changes, upon binding were derived from the known concentrations of GQDs and DNA-components, by satisfactory fitting of the parameters into the single site binding model, which signifies one type of interaction is presumably involved between GQDs and DNA components [55]. It is evident from the thermogram and binding isotherm, that interactions are exothermic in nature (Fig. 4

                        ). Further, it is to mention that no significant heat change on dilution was observed. We first demonstrated the interactions of GQDs with the nucleobases A, T and C in buffer solution. We could not study the interaction with G because of its poor solubility in water. Fig. 4 (a-c) show the ITC plot of A, T and C against GQDs in buffer solution. The interaction is exothermic for all three nucleobases. With progressive injection, the exothermicity of the peaks reduces as the number of free sites available on the GQDs surface for the binding of nucleobases decreases. As can be witnessed from the titration experiments, magnitudes of interactions of various nucleobases with GQDs are varied. To compare the binding of DNA and its different components to GQDs, the thermodynamic parameters determined so far are summarized in Table 2
                        . Complexation with different nucleobases is very enthalpically diverse though their binding parameters are very similar. The trend in the relative interaction energies in terms of enthalpy change is A > T > C, is different from that was obtained in the case of GO [25].

Eqn. (5) illustrates that the slope (α) is determining factor for enthalpic gain (δΔH) in respect of change in complex stability (δΔG). Thus, slope in the range of 0 to 1governsthe amount of conformational variation in a host − guest system as entropic loss may cancel out unfavorable enthalpy change. In contrast, intercept signifies the inherent complex stability when the enthalpic contribution, ΔH = 0. This suggests stable host − guest system even in the absence of enthalpic stabilization when TΔS0 > 0. The conformational variation and complex stabilization in a host − guest system can be assessed in quantitative terms using slope (α) and intercept (TΔS0
                        ), which have been applied in numerous supramolecular systems [60,61]. To have idea about the enthalpy–entropy compensation in interactions of ssDNA with GQDs, ITC experiments were carried out at three different temperatures (Table 3
                        ). Fig. S7 represents entropy changes (TΔS) for corresponding changes (ΔH) in enthalpy demonstrating very good linear relation with a correlation coefficient of 0.99 for the interactions of ssDNA with GQDs. The positive intercept (TΔS0 = 5.8 kcal mol−1
                        ) and near unit slope (α = 0.8) comparable to protein–ligand interaction (α = 0.96), may suggest a favorable change in conformation of ssDNA during adsorption [58]. The calculated intercept value attributed to GQDs-DNA interaction is in agreement with earlier findings on interactions of protein–nanoparticle or macromolecule–small organic molecule. Moreover, enthalpy and entropy contribution dominate primarily free energy of binding for slope > 1 or < 1, respectively [62]. Thus, the slope determined in the binding of ssDNA to GQDs suggests an entropy-driven process.
